@PennyQ @maxwelltsai - here is a simple implementation of the glue code to listen to subset additions/changes. At the moment this is not necessarily very efficient, but it should allow you now focus on the visualization.

To try this out, load a cube, then start up a 3D data viewer as well as a histogram viewer. Then, select a range in the histogram viewer. When you do this, ``QtVispyWidget.set_subsets`` will get called (you can add a print statement there to check if you like) and will be given a list of dictionaries. Each dictionary contains ``'mask'``, which is a boolean mask that is the same size/shape as the data, and indicates which pixels are selected, and the color and alpha of the selection are also passed. Then, ``set_canvas`` gets called after subset updates.

Once we merge this, you can try and see if you can modify ``set_canvas`` to highlight the subsets! :)

